@startuml
' Author: Nicholas Irvine  GitHub https://github.com/SaladStik  LinkedIn https://www.linkedin.com/in/nicholas-irvine-303ab5284/
title Orbit Delegated Auth

' nginx asks the auth service if this is allowed before it touches the
' upstream. The cookie is an opaque session id. The real session lives in Redis,
' so you can revoke it and keep it alive. The protected service never sees a token.

actor Browser
participant "nginx\n(edge, TLS)" as nginx
participant "auth\n/internal/verify" as auth
database "Redis\nsession:<id>" as redis
participant "upstream\n(auth or node-gateway)" as upstream

Browser -> nginx : GET /api/jobs\n(cookie orbit_token = opaque session id)

nginx -> auth : auth_request subrequest\n(forwards cookie only, no body)

auth -> redis : GET session:<id>
note right of redis : The cookie is an opaque id. Session data lives here, unlike a JWT.

alt session found
  redis --> auth : { user, role }
  auth -> redis : EXPIRE session:<id> (reset TTL)
  note right of auth : Sliding TTL. Each hit keeps the session alive.
  auth --> nginx : 200 + X-Auth-User
  nginx -> upstream : proxy request\n(+ trusted X-Auth-User header)
  upstream --> nginx : response
  nginx --> Browser : 200 response
else missing / expired / logged-out
  redis --> auth : (nil)
  auth --> nginx : 401
  nginx --> Browser : 401 (upstream never touched)
end

note over redis : Logout does DEL and revokes the session at once. You do not wait for expiry.
note over upstream : The upstream sees only X-Auth-User, never the cookie.

@enduml
